TY  - JOUR
T1  - Improving Interactional Organizational Research: A Model of Person-Organization Fit
AU  - Chatman, Jennifer A.
Y1  - 1989/07/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1989.4279063
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1989.4279063
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 333
EP  - 349
VL  - 14
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In order for researchers to understand and predict behavior, they must consider both person and situation factors and how these factors interact. Even though organization researchers have developed interactional models, many have overemphasized either person or situation components, and most have failed to consider the effects that persons have on situations. This paper presents criteria for improving interactional models and a model of person-organization fit, which satisfies these criteria. Using a Q-sort methodology, individual value profiles are compared to organizational value profiles to determine fit and to predict changes in values, norms, and behaviors.
AB  - In order for researchers to understand and predict behavior, they must consider both person and situation factors and how these factors interact. Even though organization researchers have developed interactional models, many have overemphasized either person or situation components, and most have failed to consider the effects that persons have on situations. This paper presents criteria for improving interactional models and a model of person-organization fit, which satisfies these criteria. Using a Q-sort methodology, individual value profiles are compared to organizational value profiles to determine fit and to predict changes in values, norms, and behaviors.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1989.4279063
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1989.4279063
